The AFM analysis (Fig. 1
                     A), showed many quantum dots (light dots) immersed in the mica, with an average diameter of GQDs ranging between 160 and 280 nm and the most frequent heights were about 5 nm. This value has been corroborated by the DLS analysis (1B). The Raman spectra revealed the presence of bands at ∼1360 cm−1 and ∼1600 cm−1 (Fig. 1C), which are the D and G characteristic bands of graphene quantum dots, associated with disorders or defects in the lattice and C-C vibrations, respectively. The X-ray diffraction analysis corroborated the formation of GQD, (Fig. 1D) with a great number of other peaks. All those peaks are due to the presence of citrate, used in the preparation of GQDs and was confirmed by the XRD analysis (Table 1
                     ).
